ble vacation experience. They explore, among other topics, issues of authenticity in Bahamian music; efforts to give tourists in Barbados peace and quiet at a former site of colonial violence; and how resort soundscapes extend beyond music to encompass the speech accents of local residents. Through interviews with resort managers, musicians, and hospitality workers, the contributors also outline the social, political, and economic pressures and interests that affect musical labor and the social encounters of musical production. In so doing, they prompt a rethinking of how to account for music and sound's resonances in postcolonial spaces.Contributors. Jerome Camal, Steven Feld, Francio Guadeloupe, Jocelyne Guilbault, Jordi Halfman, Susan Harewood, Percy C. Hintzen, Timothy Rommen  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aMusic and tourismzCaribbean Area. 0aMusicxEconomic aspectszCaribbean Area. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszCaribbean Area. 0aTourismxPolitical aspectszCaribbean Area. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aGuilbault, Jocelyne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRommen, Timothy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478005315zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478005315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478005315.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles